<span class="header1">BUSINESS ADMINISTRATION</span>
<p>In the occupations in this field, you would make sure that others
did their jobs correctly, and that the business actions ran
smoothly. If you enjoy overseeing the work of others, consider the
occupations in this field.  Here are three examples.</p>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Human Resources
Manager</span><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/CD/1372.jpg"
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Human Resource Manager">
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>A human resources manager helps to develop and
carry out a company's "people" policies.  He/she serves as a link
between employees and upper management. As a human resources
manager, you might hire or fire employees.  You might also write job
descriptions and train new employees.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>The educational backgrounds of human resources,
training, and labor relations managers and specialists vary
considerably, reflecting the diversity of duties and levels of
responsibility. In filling entry-level jobs, many employers seek
college graduates who have majored in human resources, human
resources administration, or industrial and labor relations. Other
employers look for college graduates with a technical or business
background or a well-rounded liberal arts education.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of human resources
managers was $116,720 in May 2019.
</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Employee Benefits
Manager</span><br />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>Companies often provide their employees with
benefits such as paid vacation time and health insurance. These are
called employee benefits.  Employee benefits managers and
specialists manage the company's employee benefits program, notably
its health insurance and pension plans. An employee benefits manager
helps employees to understand their benefits. She/he also helps them
to use these benefits to their advantage. As an employee benefits
manager, you would need to be well organized. You would also need to
enjoy working with people.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote> College graduates who have earned certification from professional organizations such as the International Foundation of Employee Benefit Plans
should have the best job opportunities. </blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of employee benefits
managers was $122,270 in May 2019.
</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Brokerage Clerk</span><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/CD/43328.jpg"
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Brokerage Clerk">
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>For a typical investor, buying and selling stock
is as easy as calling a broker on the phone or entering the trade
into a computer. Behind the scenes, however, buying and selling
stock is more complicated, involving trade execution and a fair
amount of paperwork. While brokers do some of this work themselves,
much of it is delegated to brokerage clerks whose tasks include
computing and recording data pertaining to securities transactions,
contacting customers, taking orders, and informing clients of
changes to their accounts.

</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>Some brokerage clerk positions require only a
high school diploma, but graduates from 2- and 4-year college degree
programs are increasingly preferred. Positions dealing with the
public, such as broker's or sales assistant, and those dealing with
more complicated financial records are especially likely to require
a college degree. </blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of brokerage clerks was
$40,540 in May 2019. </blockquote>

